 Now I will draw an example distribution. 

00:04:48.840 --> 00:04:50.740
 Let me use a different color. 

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:52.820
 This is how they are distributed 

00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:54.840
 all molecules in the system 

00:04:54.840 --> 00:04:59.240
 by number according to your speed. 

00:04:59.240 --> 00:05:00.880
 Like this, 

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:03.340
 this is the distribution of Maxwell-Boltzmann 

00:05:03.340 --> 00:05:05.172
 for this system, 

00:05:05.172 --> 00:05:07.928
 to call it system A. 

00:05:07.928 --> 00:05:10.428
 This is the one here. 

00:05:10.428 --> 00:05:14.420
 The other system, which has a lower temperature, 

00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:17.238
 which means that it has lower kinetic energy, 

00:05:17.238 --> 00:05:19.676
 there is another distribution of its particles. 

00:05:19.680 --> 00:05:22.520
 Most likely with her 

00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:24.520
 the largest number of molecules 

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:25.900
 have a lower speed. 

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:27.400
 For example, 

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:28.700
 here. 

00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:33.600
 Its distribution appears to be 

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:36.960
 in such a way. 

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:38.800
 I draw it in yellow. 

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:41.280
 Surely it seems logical, 

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:44.700
 that the speed at which I will have the most molecules 

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:47.520
 in system B will be lower, 

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:51.140
 than the speed with most molecules in system A. 

00:05:51.140 --> 00:05:54.120
 This is because the average kinetic 

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:56.040
 energy here is lower. 

00:05:56.050 --> 00:05:58.235
 The average speed is smaller. 

00:05:58.235 --> 00:06:00.184
 But why is the tip here higher? 

00:06:00.184 --> 00:06:01.800
 Let's recall the two systems 

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:03.440
 have the same number of molecules. 

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:05.350
 Thus 

00:06:05.350 --> 00:06:07.910
 the areas under both curves must be equal. 

00:06:07.910 --> 00:06:10.900
 Once this curve is narrower, it should be higher. 

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:12.760
 If we increase 

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:15.380
 the temperature of this system even more, 

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:17.780
 For example, if I warm it up 

00:06:17.780 --> 00:06:20.020
 to 400 degrees Kelvin, 

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:24.120
 then the distribution 

00:06:24.120 --> 00:06:27.470
 will be so. 

00:06:27.470 --> 00:06:30.300
 This is for a higher temperature system. 

00:06:30.300 --> 00:06:32.800
 Heated system. 

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:35.620
 This is the distribution of Maxwell-Boltzmann. 

00:06:35.620 --> 00:06:39.500
 I will not show his complex equation, 

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:41.840
 but this is its essence. 

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:43.520
 And it's a pretty logical idea. 

00:06:43.530 --> 00:06:46.010
 When you think about speed 

00:06:46.010 --> 00:06:49.600
 of individual particles, for example by air, 

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:52.060
 you may seem seemingly motionless. 

00:06:52.060 --> 00:06:54.700
 But imagining that the air around you is mostly nitrogen, 

00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:58.660
 you can understand the most probable speed 

00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:00.400
 of an arbitrary nitrogen molecule 

00:07:00.410 --> 00:07:02.618
 from the air around you. 

00:07:02.620 --> 00:07:04.220
 I will now write 

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:05.520
 its most likely speed. 

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:07.039
 You may be surprised. 

00:07:07.039 --> 00:07:10.780
 At room temperature, 

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:15.780
 possible speed 

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:20.154
 of the nitrogen molecule 

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:24.620
 at room temperature. 

00:07:24.620 --> 00:07:27.400
 Let's say this is the distribution 

00:07:27.400 --> 00:07:30.840
 of Maxwell-Boltzmann for nitrogen at room temperature. 

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:32.620
 In our example, 

00:07:32.620 --> 00:07:35.450
 that the room temperature is 300 Kelvin. 

00:07:35.450 --> 00:07:37.870
 Most likely speed 

00:07:37.870 --> 00:07:40.120
 is the one for which we have the largest number of molecules, 

00:07:40.120 --> 00:07:41.580
 who are moving 

00:07:41.580 --> 00:07:43.420
 at such a speed. 

00:07:43.620 --> 00:07:45.980
 Try first to know what it is before telling you: 

00:07:45.990 --> 00:07:47.635
 may be surprising! 

00:07:47.635 --> 00:07:49.930
 It turns out that at temperature 

00:07:49.930 --> 00:07:53.690
 300 kelvin this speed is approximately 

00:07:53.690 --> 00:07:57.846
 422 meters per second! 

00:07:57.846 --> 00:08:00.510
 A total of 422 meters in one second! 

00:08:00.510 --> 00:08:04.220
 Imagine how something goes 422 meters for just a second. 

00:08:04.220 --> 00:08:06.700
 In the more familiar unit of measurement, 

00:08:06.700 --> 00:08:12.700
 it's over 1500 kilometers per hour! 

00:08:12.730 --> 00:08:14.927
 So right now 

00:08:14.927 --> 00:08:16.850
 around you 

00:08:16.850 --> 00:08:20.120
 the largest number 

00:08:20.120 --> 00:08:22.080
 of the nitrogen molecules 

00:08:22.080 --> 00:08:24.740
 move at speed around this 

00:08:24.740 --> 00:08:26.280
 and they hit you. 

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:27.860
 This is what creates the air pressure. 

00:08:27.860 --> 00:08:29.600
 And not only at such a speed, there are molecules, 

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:31.190
 which move faster than that. 

00:08:31.190 --> 00:08:34.300
 Faster and 422 meters per second. 

00:08:34.300 --> 00:08:35.200
 Much faster. 

00:08:35.210 --> 00:08:37.730
 Some of the particles around you are moving 

00:08:37.730 --> 00:08:39.210
 thousands of miles an hour 

00:08:39.210 --> 00:08:41.980
 and they hit you in your body at that moment. 

00:08:41.980 --> 00:08:43.650
 You may wonder why it does not hurt? 

00:08:43.650 --> 00:08:47.040
 This gives you an idea of ​​how small the table is 

00:08:47.040 --> 00:08:48.870
 of the nitrogen molecule, 

00:08:48.870 --> 00:08:51.360
 when he pushes you with thousands of miles an hour 

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:52.640
 and yet you do not feel it. 

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:55.400
 It only feels like ambient air pressure. 

00:08:55.400 --> 00:08:57.020
 At first glance, it seems unimaginable: 

00:08:57.030 --> 00:08:59.300
 422 meters per second, 

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:01.510
 is this faster than the speed of the sound? 

00:09:01.510 --> 00:09:04.440
 The sound moves at approximately 340 meters per second. 

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:05.780
 How is that possible? 

00:09:05.780 --> 00:09:06.860
 Just think about it. 

00:09:06.860 --> 00:09:09.220
 The sound spreads over the air, 

00:09:09.220 --> 00:09:10.970
 by the collisions of its particles. 

00:09:10.970 --> 00:09:12.980
 Therefore, air particles, 

00:09:12.980 --> 00:09:14.780
 or at least some of them, 

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:16.780
 should move faster than the sound. 

00:09:16.780 --> 00:09:18.500
 Well, not everything around you 

00:09:18.500 --> 00:09:19.740
 is moving so fast 

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:20.840
 and in different directions; 

00:09:20.840 --> 00:09:23.280
 some particles may be almost immobile. 

00:09:23.298 --> 00:09:26.520
 But some of them move extremely fast. 

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:28.800
 Is not that great? 

